Integration tests for `ctx_verify::cli::run`'s two output modes (default terse text and `--json`), exercised through a fake `Runner` so no real `fmt`/`clippy` subprocess is invoked.

`FakeRunner` maps the first CLI arg of a command (e.g. `"fmt"`, `"clippy"`) to a canned `Option<CommandOutcome>`: `Some(outcome)` returns it, `None` or an absent key yields `Err(CheckError::ToolMissing(key))` — this is how tests simulate a missing tool. The `render` helper parses argv via `Cli::try_parse_from`, runs `cli::run` against the fake runner writing to an in-memory `Vec<u8>`, and returns `(passed, stdout_string)`; it returns `Result` (not a panicking helper) specifically so it can be called from inside `#[test]` fns without violating the crate's unwrap/expect ban, with callers using `.expect("render")` at the call site instead.

Key invariants asserted here, load-bearing for `cli::run`'s contract: terse pass output is exactly `"pass\n"` (single line, no trailing content); terse failure output starts with a `FAIL: <check> (<count>)` header, formats each diagnostic as `<file>:<line>  <code>: <message>`, and truncates diagnostics beyond `--max-diagnostics` with a `"… +N more"` tail; terse failure output must never contain `"status"` — i.e., JSON must not leak into terse mode even on failure. The `--json` mode instead emits a value parseable by `serde_json` with a top-level `"status"` field (`"pass"`/likely `"fail"`).

The clippy diagnostic fixture is hand-built as literal JSON lines matching cargo's `compiler-message` wire format (`reason`, `message.level`, `message.code.code`, `message.spans[].{is_primary,file_name,line_start,column_start}`) — this must stay in sync with whatever struct in the crate (likely `diagnostics.rs` or similar) deserializes clippy/cargo JSON output; if that struct's field names or nesting change, this fixture breaks silently unless the test is rerun.